<article xml:id="session10wks" label="5107">

  <title>MATH 142 Hands-On, Grades Up</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      For workspace between exercises, print this worksheet or download to your device by clicking the printer icon.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <worksheet>

    <title>Session #10 (3.4 - 3.5, 4.1 - 4.4)</title>
    <p>
      Directions: Answer each of the following as best you can. Feel free to discuss your thoughts about the questions with some peers around you. 
      For additional practice problems and explanations, refer to the Math 142 textbook which is free and can be downloaded as a PDF 
      at <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa"> Texas A&amp;M The OAKTrust Digital Repository </url>.
      <!--'&' and '<' are exceptional characters and are instead authored as &lt; and &amp;. See 4.1.4.2-->
    </p>

    <paragraphs>

      <title>Getting Warmed Up and in the Right Mindset</title>

      <exercise workspace="2in">

        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the graph of <m>g^\prime(x)</m> given below and shade in the area represented by
            <m>\int_0^5 g^\prime(x)\,dx</m>.
          </p>

          <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session10_Fig1.png"
                 width="40%"/>
        </statement>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in">

        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the graph of <m>g^\prime(x)</m> given below and shade in the area represented by
            <m>\int_7^{13} g^\prime(x)\,dx</m>.
          </p>

          <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session10_Fig1.png"
                 width="40%"/>
        </statement>

      </exercise>

    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>

      <title>Let Us Get Our Hands On</title>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="1">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Given the graph of <m>g'(x)</m> below, compute the integrals below.
          </p>

          <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session10_Fig1.png"
                 width="40%"/>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_0^2 g^\prime(x)\,dx</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_5^9 g^\prime(x)\,dx</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_0^{13} g^\prime(x)\,dx</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="2">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Consider the function <m>f(x)=-\frac{1}{4}x^2+1</m>.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Sketch a graph of <m>f(x)</m> and use your sketch to draw the rectangles that represent the right-hand Riemann sum on
              <m>[-2,0]</m>
              using <m>4</m> subintervals of equal width.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Estimate the area under the curve of <m>f(x)</m> over the interval <m>[-2,0]</m> using a right-hand Riemann sum with <m>4</m> subintervals of equal width. Is this an overestimate or an underestimate?
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              State the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part 2 (see page 709 of your textbook).
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part 2 to find the exact value of
              <m>\int_{-2}^0 f(x)\,dx</m>.
              How does this compare to your answer in part (b)?
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="3">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Evaluate each of the following definite integrals exactly. Leave all answers in exact form.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_{-2}^2 (x^3-3x^2+3x-1)\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_3^7 \sqrt{x-3}\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_0^3 \frac{6x}{(x^2+1)^2}\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_0^{\sqrt{10}} \frac{4x}{9+x^2}\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="4">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Find all values of <m>A</m> such that:
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_2^4 (x^3+3x^2+A)\,dx = 12</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_{-1}^1 Ax\,dx = -3</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int_{e^A}^7 \frac{1}{x}\,dx = 5</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="5">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            A local bagel shop's marginal profit is given by
            <m>p^\prime(x)=0.05x^2-2.1x+100</m>
            dollars per bagel when <m>x</m> bagels are sold.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Estimate the change in profit when the number of bagels increases from <m>50</m> to <m>59</m> using <m>3</m> subintervals of equal width and a left Riemann sum.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the exact change in profit when the number of bagels increases from <m>50</m> to <m>59</m> using the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part 2.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="6">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            A company sells <m>x</m> handbags per year priced at <m>\$p</m> per handbag. The company's price-demand function for the handbags is given by
            <m>p(x)=100-0.05x</m>.
            Each handbag costs <m>\$15</m> to manufacture and the company has fixed costs of <m>\$12{,}000</m> per year.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is the yearly cost function <m>C(x)</m>?
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is the yearly revenue function <m>R(x)</m>?
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use parts (a) and (b) to determine the yearly profit function <m>P(x)</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find a reasonable domain to restrict <m>P(x)</m> to.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              How many handbags must the company sell to maximize its profit? What is the company's maximum profit?
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="7">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            A manufacturer needs to make a closed cylindrical can that will hold <m>1500</m> cm<sup>3</sup> of water. Determine the dimensions (in cm) of the can that will use the least amount of material.
          </p>

          <p>
            (Hint: The formula for the volume of a cylinder is
            <m>V=\pi r^2h</m>
            and the formula for the surface area of a cylinder is
            <m>A=2\pi rh+2\pi r^2</m>.)
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Is this a maximum or minimum problem?
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is to be maximized/minimized?
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Formulate the objective function.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Formulate any constraint equations.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find any critical values of the objective function.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Provide the final answer (with units).
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="8">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Consider the function <m>f^\prime(x)=3e^x-x^{3/2}+1</m>.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the general anti-derivative of <m>f^\prime(x)</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the constant of integration <m>C</m> given <m>f(0)=2</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="9">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Consider the function
            <m>h(x)=x^3+\frac{3}{2}x^2-18x</m>.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find all absolute extrema of <m>h(x)</m> on <m>[-6,4]</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find all absolute extrema of <m>h(x)</m> on <m>(-6,0)</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>

      <title>Now Grades Go Up</title>

      <exercise workspace="1.5in" number="1">

        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose the area under the curve <m>g'(x)</m> from <m>x=a</m> to <m>x=b</m> is <m>17</m>. If we know <m>g(b)=9</m>, find <m>g(a)</m>.
          </p>

          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li><p><m>g(a)=-8</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>g(a)=26</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>g(a)=8</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>g(a)=-26</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>g(a)=17/9</m></p></li>
          </ol>

        </statement>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="1.5in" number="2">

        <statement>
          <p>
            Given that <m>f(x)</m> is a continuous function,
            <m>\int_{-2}^{3} f(x)\,dx=-4</m>,
            and
            <m>\int_{0}^{-2} f(x)\,dx=7</m>,
            find
            <m>\int_0^3 (2x+f(x))\,dx</m>.
          </p>

          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li><p><m>9</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>-2</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>-11</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>12</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>19</m></p></li>
          </ol>

        </statement>

      </exercise>

    </paragraphs>

  </worksheet>

</article>

